metadata.name: C-SCAPE #230
metadata.description:
Cellular Automata are one of the oldest and simplest classes of generative systems. Beginning with the highly abstracted, reductionist models of artificial life research by Stanislav Ulam and John von Neumann in the 1940s, Barricelli in the early 1950s, then re-discovered, formalized, expanded and popularized by other mathematicians like Conway and Wolfram 20-30 years later, it's a long-running field of research, rich with unexpected surprises and new discoveries. C-SCAPE is (a partial) result of over 20 years of my own explorations and a celebration of these simple systems.

Most of my purely generative work has been about creating and harnessing emergent complexity & nonrepetitve, ever-changing behaviors (and their interactions) borne from extremely simple systems, mechanisms, algorithms & languages: Exposing, investigating (and yes, celebrating) generativity in its raw form. By minimizing, though not entirely avoiding, additional human aesthetic decision making (here primarily in the form of curating automata rules & color themes), I'm trying to focus the observer on the raw beauty of the underlying processes and bring it to the fore. My hope is, this too will lead viewers asking themselves the deeper questions about the nature of rules, behavior, order and complexity in their own lives, esp. in the current rising polarizing political & anti-science climate. Furthermore, I'd like to provide a counter point and emphasize the unique qualities of generative art, compared to other, more figurative and abstract art approaches.

C-SCAPE simulates a shared toroidal environment in which multiple cellular automata (CA) are evolving and influencing each other, forming short-lived symbioses and/or wiping each other out, only to be restored again later on. The automata are all operating on a single row of pixels at a time and therefore are only 1-dimensional. Yet, many of them also have a short term memory and can produce more complex structures/behaviors by utilizing their memory of previous cell states. Each individually minted version produces a unique system which evolves over time and never repeats.

The final selection of CA rules used in this piece is the result of many years of experimentation with 100,000s of different configurations and many (manual) review/pruning/cataloging sessions to encourage the minted editions to cover a interesting & balanced subset of the more than duodecillion (10^39) possible individual structures & textures (not including interactions and/or color variations)...

Viewing

The piece in best viewed in medium/high resolution landscape format. The horizontal resolution should be at the very least 800 pixels, preferably double that or higher. There's a max. pixel resolution limit of 4096 pixels in either direction, but CPU performance might suffer at these resolutions. On narrow/mobile portrait ratios the piece will be shown 90 degrees rotated and is scrolling sideways.

Controls

- x : export current frame
- r : randomize environment

License

https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/

Disclaimer

Minting this project will not guarantee inclusion in access lists for future projects.

Credits

Made in 2022 with <3 and thi.ng

metadata.name: A24Z #737
metadata.description:
Every artist and collector feels the joy of both creating and collecting. But if I could share the joy of creating with collectors. And collectors with their family and friends, what may be an additive process of joy is now perhaps exponential. Joy to the power of 26 to be exact. 

In this work I invite my friends and collectors to collaborate with me. Though not in coding, but together in a process of creating narratives and visuals. Code and story. We didn’t use github, just a simple p5.js editor to try out different programs and palettes. Pedrofe and J0rdan pick their palettes tastefully and carefully. okeoke, perhaps more of a genius than he lets on, picks his palettes blind. No hex color picker. Just straight up rhymes.  

In our discussions verbal language was forbidden. Only emojis were allowed to express our tastes and views. Each emojis put down on google doc was taken with absolutely seriousness. 

Pedro: Loves to taking his daily walks on “Magic Mushroom Mountain”

J0rdan: Wonders about “Quark Question Quiches”

Okeoke: Just get lost in “Finnegans’ Flower Fields.”

It has been a great joy to present our illustration book A24Z, 8 more than you know who. Each page expresses the alphabet with the best of our knowledge in semantics and sarcasm. Collect just 1 page, collect the alphabets that spell out your name, collect the whole A to Z. Read it to your children or loved ones. Though you might need to interpolate or extrapolate with great imagination which children all have. But most importantly, like all children, have fun!

Press 1 to save png, only for Chrome, not Safari. Preview images are compressed or broken, test capture at 300 sec.

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Pines #42
metadata.description:
A combination of pine trees, hills and mountains put together in a way that represents nature in it's true form.

Everything is generated by code by drawing pixels on a canvas using Javascript.
The simplex-noise library was used to generate the hills and the mountains.

I hope you like this piece!

metadata.name: Rearranged #38
metadata.description:
Rearranged is an invitation to engage in an exploration of aesthetics within the constraints of the generated token. 

Each piece has 4 layers. Each layer can be independently rotated by 90 degrees clockwise by clicking 1,2,3 or 4 on the keyboard. Some changes are subtle. Some are surprising. 

's' on the keyboard will scramble all of the rotations.
'r' will reset to the original artwork.

You are invited to: 
arrange a more aesthetically pleasing piece than the original;
scramble the artwork and use the number keys to return it to its original state;
work out which shapes have been erased from each layer.

And of course there is also a gorgeous gradient illusion made of solid-colour filled tessellating shapes. 

3 tessellations of varying sizes, 12 layouts with random elements, 14 palettes.

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Tumble Down Light Factory #322
metadata.description:
Tumble Down Light Factory is an interpretation of light installations & murals.

It attempts to trigger the feeling of coming up on a new block in a new city to discover an unexpected piece of art that is stories tall or entering a new room, knowing there will be a projection dominating the space with its light and color.

This is an abstract distillation of those things and those feelings.

Each composition is initially drawn to a hidden “template” canvas which is sampled and then rendered on the main canvas in various ways after applying some transforms to give it some depth (and so you can actually see it.)

Viewing in full-screen is nice. You should try it.

T : Save hidden ‘template’ image
S : Save current resolution
1 -> 5 : Save low -> high resolution

metadata.name: Not a Planet #72
metadata.description:
Abstract composition based on waves contained inside a circle.

Features:
- Style of the edges (clean or irregular)
- Style of the waves (Normal, Spikes, Mixed)
- Completeness of the wave (true or false)
- Palette

Made with p5.js

Note:
- Press ‘e' in Live View to save a png.

metadata.name: Mirror Mirror #80
metadata.description:
Stare into the abyss with endlessly repeating forms twisting into the infinity defined by perlin randomness. This project is inspired by early childhood memories looking into two mirrors and playing with reflections forever.

Mirror Mirror is a generative project with a digital output, but it has a second life as a physical IRL object that can be cut from 12 layers of wood or plotted on paper.

24 free physicals will be attached at random to mints.
Learn more about physicals: https://alleditions.art/p/mirrormirror

SPECIAL FEATURES
- Shift-P: exports a PNG
- Shift-E: explodes the layers
- Shift-S: Exports an SVG
- A, S, D, & W: skew the layers
- ?screws=true: add some holes for Chicago screws

metadata.name: Celestial Objects #14
metadata.description:
Celestial Objects is a generative collection imagining planets and stars in the space, with light and shadows being key themes. 

The artwork is primarily rendered using hundreds of thousands of points (more than a million in some cases) to create different aspects of the output including the sky textures, shooting stars and shadows on the planets. 

Celestial Objects is coded in p5.js, and please note that it takes 5-15 seconds for each output to render.

Controls (in live view): 
Press [2] to render 2000x2000px image
Press [4] to render 4000x4000px image
Press [s] to save the current view (default window size or 2000px or 4000px image)

metadata.name: JazzConnectible #14
metadata.description:
JazzConnectible
Improvisation at the core.

The JazzConnectible collection is a continuation of the artist’s exploration of the possibilities of the time-based generative art on the example of her own original development - ⚡ Generative Connectibles⚡ . 

What's new?

 - New blocks, new connections;
 - 10 color skins /themes/. Each theme contains 1-5 palettes;
 - The algorithm has been trained to improvise! 

Jazz is what it should be!



Animation saving works in test mode (Chrome only): press 'open live' button, press 'S', wait 10-15 seconds. The saved GIF will open in a pop-up window or a new tab.
